    <section id="challenge">
      <title>Breaking the Shoreline Constraint</title>
      <sectiondiv>
        <p><b>The Challenge</b></p>
        <p>Conventional chip I/O is confined to the die edges, known in the industry as the
          shoreline. As die area scales with the square of the radius, perimeter scales only
          linearly, creating a bandwidth bottleneck. Chips exhaust edge space long before they
          exhaust compute capability.</p>
      </sectiondiv>
      <sectiondiv>
        <p><b><keyword keyref="lm-passage-l200"/> Implementation</b></p>
        <p><keyword keyref="lm-passage-l200-tm"/> removes this constraint by vertically integrating
          the photonic IC (PIC) beneath the electronic IC (EIC). This places SerDes and optical
          interfaces across the entire die surface, enabling bandwidth density that scales with
          silicon area rather than die perimeter.</p>
      </sectiondiv>
    </section>

  </body>
